    Mechanism: Selective inhibition of IL17A and IL17F expression via modulation of epigenetic modifications (through HDAC inhibitors reducing histone acetylation) decreases the activation of cytokine signaling pathways. Concurrently, the upregulation of immune-regulatory microRNAs such as miR-146a downregulates key intermediate signaling mediators (e.g., IRAK1, TRAF6), thereby reducing the activation of transcription factors and overall NF-kB pathway activity.

    Expected Outcomes: Significant reduction in IL-17A and IL-17F gene expression in RA synovial cells., Decreased activation of the NF-kB pathway as measured by reporter assays and reduced nuclear translocation of NF-kB subunits., Lower levels of pro-inflammatory cytokines (e.g., TNF-alpha, IL-6) in treated cell cultures and animal models., Enhanced therapeutic efficacy in RA animal models when combining HDAC inhibitors with miRNA mimics compared to either treatment alone.

